<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 12 — Conditional Proof and Indirect Proof

  Draft status:
  - Building section by section.
  - CP and IP are proof strategies, not new rules of inference.
  - Proof format based on the lead author's handwritten notation:
    indented scope with vertical line, "Assume for CP/IP",
    discharge citing line range.
  - IP produces ~(the assumption): one tilde prepended.
  - IP requires an explicit contradiction (P · ~P) via Conj.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-conditional-indirect-proof">

  <title>Conditional Proof and Indirect Proof</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-cp-ip-intro">
    <p>
      Every valid sentential argument can be proven valid using the
      eighteen rules from Chapters 10 and 11. That is a mathematical
      fact, and it is meant to be reassuring. But if you have worked
      the exercises in those chapters, you know that <q>can be
      proven</q> and <q>can be proven without losing your mind</q>
      are different claims. Some proofs are brutally hard to find
      when all you can do is derive new lines from old ones. The
      conclusion does not appear anywhere in the premises. No rule
      seems to produce it. You try everything, and nothing connects.
    </p>
    <p>
      This chapter introduces two strategies that solve that problem.
      <term>Conditional Proof</term> (CP) and
      <term>Indirect Proof</term> (IP) are not new rules of
      inference — they do not add to the eighteen. They are
      strategies for <em>organizing</em> a proof. Both work by
      letting you <em>temporarily assume</em> something, derive
      consequences from that assumption using the eighteen rules you
      already know, and then <em>discharge</em> the assumption to
      reach a conclusion you could not have reached directly.
    </p>
    <p>
      If the eighteen rules are the tools in your toolbox,
      Conditional Proof and Indirect Proof are the techniques that
      tell you how to hold the tools when the usual grip does not
      work.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-two-new-strategies">
    <title>Two New Strategies</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Before we learn either strategy in detail, we need to
        understand what they have in common and why they exist.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-ip-not-rules">
      <title>Strategies, not rules</title>
      <p>
        An implication rule like Modus Ponens tells you: <q>given
        these inputs, you may write this output.</q> A replacement
        rule like De Morgan's tells you: <q>this expression may be
        rewritten as that expression.</q> CP and IP do something
        different. They tell you: <q>you may temporarily assume a
        statement, work inside that assumption, and then close the
        assumption to reach a conclusion.</q>
      </p>
      <p>
        The key word is <em>temporarily</em>. When you make an
        assumption for CP or IP, you open a <term>scope</term> — a
        bounded region of the proof where the assumption is in
        play. Inside that scope, you may use any of the eighteen
        rules, and you may also use lines from before the scope
        opened. But when the scope closes, the assumption is
        <term>discharged</term>, and the lines inside the scope
        are no longer available. You cannot cite them in later
        steps. They did their work; now they are sealed off.
      </p>
      <p>
        Think of it this way. A scope is like a thought experiment.
        You say: <q>Suppose this were true. What would follow?</q>
        You work out the consequences. Then you step back out of the
        experiment and report what you learned — not the individual
        steps inside, but the overall conclusion that the experiment
        established.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-scope-format">
      <title>How scopes look on the page</title>
      <p>
        In this course, a scope is marked by <alert>indentation and
        a vertical line</alert> running along the left side of the
        scoped lines. The first line of the scope is the assumption.
        The last line is the final result derived inside the scope.
        When the scope closes, the next line returns to the original
        indentation level, and its justification cites the line
        range of the scope plus the strategy name (CP or IP).
      </p>
      <p>
        Here is the skeleton, with no specific formulas — just the
        shape:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-scope-skeleton">
        <title>Scope Skeleton</title>
        <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
          <row><cell>1.</cell><cell>(premise)</cell><cell></cell></row>
          <row><cell>2.</cell><cell>(premise)</cell><cell>/ (target)</cell></row>
          <row bottom="minor"><cell>3.</cell><cell>(derived line)</cell><cell>(justification)</cell></row>

          <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| (assumption)</cell><cell>Assume for CP/IP</cell></row>
          <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| (derived)</cell><cell>(justification)</cell></row>
          <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| (derived)</cell><cell>(justification)</cell></row>

          <row><cell>7.</cell><cell>(conclusion)</cell><cell>4–6 CP/IP</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Lines 4–6 are inside the scope. Line 7 discharges the
        assumption: it cites the range (4–6) and the strategy.
        After line 7, you may not cite lines 4, 5, or 6 in any
        further steps.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-when-cp-when-ip">
      <title>When to use which</title>
      <p>
        The decision is usually straightforward:
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Use Conditional Proof when your target is a
        conditional.</alert> If the conclusion you need is
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>, assume
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m> (the antecedent), derive
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m> (the consequent) inside the scope, and
        discharge. CP hands you the conditional.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Use Indirect Proof when direct proof is stuck and the
        target is not a conditional</alert> (or when it is, but CP
        is not working). Assume the negation of what you want to
        prove, derive an explicit contradiction inside the scope,
        and discharge. IP hands you the negation of your assumption.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most proofs at this level need only one of the two. A few
        need both. We will take them one at a time.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-conditional-proof">
    <title>Conditional Proof</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Conditional Proof is the more intuitive of the two
        strategies, and it is usually the one students reach for
        first. The idea is simple: if you want to prove a
        conditional, assume its antecedent and show that the
        consequent follows.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-procedure">
      <title>The CP procedure</title>
      <p>
        Suppose your target is
        <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>. Here is the
        procedure:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Assume <m>\mathcal{A}</m>.</alert> Write
          <m>\mathcal{A}</m> on a new line. Its justification is
          <q>Assume for CP.</q> This opens a scope.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Derive <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.</alert> Inside the
          scope, use the eighteen rules plus any lines from before
          the scope to derive <m>\mathcal{B}</m>. You may take as
          many steps as you need.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Discharge.</alert> Close the scope. On the next
          line (back at the original indentation), write
          <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>. Its justification
          cites the line range of the scope and the label CP.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That is the entire strategy. Assume the antecedent, derive
        the consequent, discharge the conditional. Everything inside
        the scope is sealed off after discharge.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-simple-example">
      <title>A simple CP proof</title>
      <p>
        Consider this argument:
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-cp-simple">
        <title>A two-premise CP proof</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-cp-simple">
            <title>Deriving <m>P \supset R</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>

              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,3 MP</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>2,4 MP</cell></row>

              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>3–5 CP</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        You might notice that this argument can also be proven in
        one step by Hypothetical Syllogism (lines 1 and 2 give
        <m>P \supset R</m> by HS). That is true, and in practice
        you should use HS when it works. But the CP proof illustrates
        the strategy clearly: assume <m>P</m> (the antecedent of the
        target), derive <m>R</m> (the consequent) by chaining MP
        twice, then discharge.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-full-example">
      <title>A longer CP proof</title>
      <p>
        Now a proof where CP earns its keep — where the conclusion
        is a conditional and no direct path is obvious.
      </p>
      <example xml:id="ex-cp-full">
        <title>CP with replacement rules</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-cp-full">
            <title>Deriving <m>R \supset S</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>(R \cdot Q) \supset S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R \supset S</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>1 DeM</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>4 Impl</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>5 DN</cell></row>
              <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>6 Trans</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>8.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>2,7 HS</cell></row>

              <row><cell>9.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>10.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>9 DN</cell></row>
              <row><cell>11.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>8,10 MT</cell></row>
              <row><cell>12.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>11 DN</cell></row>
              <row><cell>13.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>R \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>9,12 Conj</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>14.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>S</m></cell><cell>3,13 MP</cell></row>

              <row><cell>15.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell>9–14 CP</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        This proof has two phases. Lines 1–8 are setup: replacement
        rules reshape the premises into forms that will be useful
        inside the scope. Lines 9–14 are the CP scope: we assume
        <m>R</m> (the antecedent of the target
        <m>R \supset S</m>), use the reshaped premises to derive
        <m>Q</m>, combine <m>R</m> and <m>Q</m> into the
        conjunction that line 3 needs, and MP gives us <m>S</m>.
        Line 15 discharges: <m>R \supset S</m>, citing lines 9–14.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice that the scope used lines from <em>before</em> the
        scope opened — lines 3 and 8 were both cited from inside
        the scope. That is always permitted. Lines before the scope
        are established facts, not assumptions. What you cannot do
        is cite lines from inside a closed scope after it closes.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-notes">
      <title>Notes on Conditional Proof</title>
      <p>
        <alert>You can use CP even when the target is not a
        conditional.</alert> Occasionally a proof benefits from
        establishing an intermediate conditional via CP, then using
        that conditional in subsequent steps. This is legal. CP
        produces a conditional; what you do with it afterward is up
        to you.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>What you assume matters.</alert> For CP, you always
        assume the antecedent of the conditional you want to
        produce. If your target is <m>P \supset Q</m>, assume
        <m>P</m>. If your target is
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R \supset S</m>, assume
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m>. The assumption determines
        the left side of the conditional you get when you discharge.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Do not forget to discharge.</alert> A proof that ends
        inside an open scope is not a completed proof. The scope must
        close, and the discharge line must appear at the original
        indentation level with the CP justification.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-indirect-proof">
    <title>Indirect Proof</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Indirect Proof is the strategy you reach for when you want
        to prove something and no direct path works. The idea has a
        long history in mathematics and philosophy: assume the
        opposite of what you want to prove, show that the opposite
        leads to a contradiction, and conclude that the opposite
        must be false — which means what you wanted to prove must
        be true. Logicians sometimes call it <em>reductio ad
        absurdum</em>: reduction to absurdity. You assume something,
        blow it up, and walk away with the negation.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ip-procedure">
      <title>The IP procedure</title>
      <p>
        Suppose you want to prove <m>\mathcal{A}</m>. Here is the
        procedure:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Assume
          <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m>.</alert> Write
          the negation of what you want to prove on a new line. Its
          justification is <q>Assume for IP.</q> This opens a scope.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Derive a contradiction.</alert> Inside the scope,
          use the eighteen rules plus any lines from before the
          scope to derive two lines: some statement
          <m>\mathcal{B}</m> and its negation
          <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>. Then join
          them into an <em>explicit</em> contradiction using
          Conjunction:
          <m>\mathcal{B} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Discharge.</alert> Close the scope. On the next
          line (back at the original indentation), write
          <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m> followed by whatever
          appeared on the assumption line. Its justification cites
          the line range of the scope and the label IP.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Read step 3 carefully.
        <alert>IP gives you one tilde prepended to the assumption
        line.</alert> If your assumption was
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>, then IP gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.
        If your assumption was <m>P</m>, then IP gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. The discharge line is
        always: tilde + whatever you assumed. This means that if you
        assumed a negation (which is the usual case, since you
        typically assume the negation of your target), you will need
        Double Negation as a cleanup step after IP to remove the
        double tilde and reach your target.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ip-contradiction-explicit">
      <title>The contradiction must be explicit</title>
      <p>
        This is a point students sometimes miss.
        It is not enough to derive two lines that happen to
        contradict each other. You must <em>build</em> the
        contradiction on a single line using Conjunction. The
        contradiction takes the form
        <m>\mathcal{B} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>
        — a statement conjoined with its own negation. If you have
        <m>S</m> on one line and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> on another, you must write
        <m>S \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> (or
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S \cdot S</m> — order does not
        matter) using Conj before you can discharge. The explicit
        conjunction is what licenses the discharge.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ip-simple-example">
      <title>A simple IP proof</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-ip-simple">
        <title>A short Indirect Proof</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-ip-simple">
            <title>Deriving <m>P</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P</m></cell></row>

              <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,3 MP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>2,3 MP</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>4,5 Conj</cell></row>

              <row><cell>7.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>3–6 IP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>8.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>7 DN</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        Walk through it. We want <m>P</m>. We assume
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> (the negation of our
        target). From that assumption and the two premises, MP gives
        us both <m>Q</m> (line 4) and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m> (line 5). We conjoin them
        into the explicit contradiction
        <m>Q \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m> (line 6). The
        assumption led to absurdity, so we discharge: IP gives us
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>
        (line 7) — one tilde prepended to the assumption
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. Double Negation cleans
        it up to <m>P</m> (line 8).
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ip-full-example">
      <title>A longer IP proof</title>
      <example xml:id="ex-ip-full">
        <title>IP with setup work</title>
        <statement>
          <table xml:id="table-ex-ip-full">
            <title>Deriving <m>Q</m></title>
            <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
              <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>({\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}S) \cdot ({\text{\textasciitilde}}S \supset S)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
              <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S \supset S</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>

              <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell>2,4 MP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>S</m></cell><cell>3,5 MP</cell></row>
              <row bottom="minor"><cell>7.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>S \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell>5,6 Conj</cell></row>

              <row><cell>8.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>4–7 IP</cell></row>
              <row><cell>9.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>8 DN</cell></row>
            </tabular>
          </table>
        </statement>
      </example>
      <p>
        The target is <m>Q</m>, and it does not appear anywhere in
        the premise. There is no conditional with <m>Q</m> as a
        consequent, no disjunction with <m>Q</m> as a disjunct.
        Direct proof has nothing to work with. IP solves the problem.
      </p>
      <p>
        We assume <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>. From that
        assumption, MP with line 2 gives
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>. From
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>, MP with line 3 gives
        <m>S</m>. Now we have both <m>S</m> and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>. We conjoin them into the
        explicit contradiction
        <m>S \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> (line 7). IP
        discharges:
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>
        (line 8) — one tilde prepended to the assumption
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>. DN gives us <m>Q</m>
        (line 9).
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-ip-notes">
      <title>Notes on Indirect Proof</title>
      <p>
        <alert>IP always produces ~(the assumption).</alert> This
        is worth repeating because it is the single most confusing
        aspect of IP. The discharge line is not the target. The
        discharge line is one tilde prepended to whatever appeared
        on the assumption line. If the assumption was
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>, the discharge gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>,
        and you need DN to reach <m>Q</m>. If the assumption was
        <m>P</m>, the discharge gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, and that might be your
        target directly.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Any contradiction will do.</alert> The contradiction
        does not have to involve the assumption or the target. If
        your assumption leads to a world where
        <m>R \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m> is derivable,
        that is a perfectly good contradiction even if <m>R</m>
        has nothing to do with what you are trying to prove. A
        contradiction is a contradiction; the universe does not
        care which statement was contradicted.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Choose your contradiction strategically.</alert>
        That said, some contradictions are easier to reach than
        others. Look at what the assumption gives you access to.
        If assuming <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m> lets you
        derive both <m>S</m> and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> in two steps, use that
        pair. Do not hunt for a more elegant contradiction when a
        fast one is available.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Build the conjunction.</alert> Do not skip the
        Conj step. Even if you have <m>S</m> on line 6 and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> on line 5, you must
        write
        <m>S \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> on a new line
        using Conj before you discharge. The explicit conjunction
        is the trigger for IP. (Think of it as showing your work.
        The contradiction has to be on the page, not just in your
        head.)
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-cp-ip-strategy">
    <title>Choosing and Using CP and IP</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        You now know the mechanics of both strategies. This section
        gives you a decision procedure for choosing between them and
        warns you about the mistakes that cost students the most
        points.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-ip-decision">
      <title>The decision procedure</title>
      <p>
        When you sit down with a proof, ask yourself these questions
        in order:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Can you prove it directly?</alert> Scan the
          premises. If you see a clear path using the eighteen rules
          alone, take it. CP and IP are powerful, but unnecessary
          complexity is still unnecessary.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Is the target a conditional?</alert> If yes, try
          CP. Assume the antecedent, try to derive the consequent.
          CP is almost always the right move when the conclusion has
          <m>\supset</m> as its main connective.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Is direct proof stuck and the target is not a
          conditional?</alert> Try IP. Assume the negation of the
          target and hunt for a contradiction.
        </p></li>
        <li><p>
          <alert>Is the target a conditional but CP is not
          working?</alert> Try IP instead. Assume the negation of
          the entire conditional (which you can then break apart
          with De Morgan's or Material Implication) and look for a
          contradiction. This is rarer but sometimes necessary.
        </p></li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Most proofs at this level are settled by questions 1–3. If
        you reach question 4, the proof is likely one of the harder
        exercises, and that is okay — you have the tools for it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-ip-common-errors">
      <title>Common errors</title>
      <p>
        <alert>Citing a scoped line after the scope closes.</alert>
        This is the most common CP/IP error. Once you discharge, the
        lines inside the scope are sealed off. If line 5 was inside
        a scope that closed at line 8, you cannot cite line 5 on
        line 9 or later. The scope did its job; its internal lines
        no longer exist as available resources.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Forgetting to discharge.</alert> A proof that ends
        inside an open scope is incomplete. The last line of your
        proof must be at the original indentation level. If you
        derived the consequent inside a CP scope, you still need
        the discharge line that produces the conditional.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Skipping the explicit contradiction in IP.</alert>
        You must build the conjunction
        <m>\mathcal{B} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>
        on a line inside the scope using Conj. Having
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m> on one line and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m> on another is
        not enough. Write the conjunction.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Confusing what IP produces.</alert> IP gives you
        one tilde prepended to the assumption. It does not give you
        the target directly (unless the target happens to be the
        negation of the assumption). If you assumed
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, IP gives you
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>.
        You still need DN to get <m>P</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <alert>Assuming the wrong thing for CP.</alert> For CP, you
        assume the <em>antecedent</em> of the conditional you want.
        If your target is <m>P \supset Q</m>, assume <m>P</m>, not
        <m>Q</m>, and not
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. The assumption becomes
        the left side of the conditional you get when you discharge.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-cp-ip-nesting">
      <title>Can you nest scopes?</title>
      <p>
        Yes. You can open a CP scope inside an IP scope, or an IP
        scope inside a CP scope, or even a CP inside a CP. Each
        scope must be properly closed before the enclosing scope
        closes, and the same rule applies: lines inside a closed
        inner scope cannot be cited outside it.
      </p>
      <p>
        Nested scopes are rare at this level. If you find yourself
        nesting, step back and ask whether a simpler approach
        exists. But if the proof genuinely requires it, the
        mechanics are the same — just keep the indentation clean
        and close scopes in the right order.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-12-4-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Reflect on the decision to assume</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose a proof from this chapter's exercises where you
          used CP or IP. Reconstruct the moment you decided to open
          a scope. What were you looking at? What told you that
          direct proof wasn't going to work? Was the decision
          immediate or did you try direct proof first and then
          switch? Write a short account of that decision.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-cp-ip-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      This chapter completes the sentential logic toolkit. You now
      have eighteen rules of inference plus two proof strategies.
      Every valid argument in sentential logic can be proven with
      these resources — and with CP and IP available, most proofs
      that would have been painfully long are now manageable.
    </p>
    <p>
      Part IV of this book shifts direction. Sentential logic asks
      whether conclusions follow <em>necessarily</em> from premises.
      Inductive and statistical reasoning asks a different question:
      how <em>strongly</em> do the premises support the conclusion?
      The tools change — no more proof lines and rule citations — but
      the underlying project is the same one we started in Chapter 1:
      evaluating whether reasons are good reasons for believing what
      they claim to support.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch-cp-ip">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced Conditional Proof and Indirect Proof
      as strategies for organizing proofs that the eighteen rules
      alone make difficult.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Two New Strategies (§12.1).</alert> CP and IP are not
      new rules of inference. They are strategies that let you
      temporarily assume a statement, work inside a bounded scope,
      and discharge the assumption to reach a conclusion. Lines
      inside a closed scope cannot be cited afterward.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Conditional Proof (§12.2).</alert> When the target is a
      conditional <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m>, assume the
      antecedent <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, derive the consequent
      <m>\mathcal{B}</m> inside the scope, and discharge to obtain
      the conditional. Justification: <q>Assume for CP</q> on the
      assumption line; <q>n–m CP</q> on the discharge line.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Indirect Proof (§12.3).</alert> When direct proof is
      stuck, assume the negation of the target, derive an explicit
      contradiction
      (<m>\mathcal{B} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>
      via Conj) inside the scope, and discharge. IP produces one
      tilde prepended to the assumption. DN is typically needed
      afterward to reach the target. Justification: <q>Assume for
      IP</q> on the assumption line; <q>n–m IP</q> on the discharge
      line.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Choosing and Using CP and IP (§12.4).</alert> Try direct
      proof first. If the target is a conditional, try CP. If direct
      proof is stuck and the target is not a conditional, try IP.
      Common errors include citing scoped lines after discharge,
      forgetting to discharge, skipping the explicit conjunction in
      IP, and confusing what IP produces.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch12-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-assumption">
        <title>Assumption</title>
        <p>A statement temporarily introduced at the start of a CP or IP scope, serving as a hypothesis from which consequences are derived. (§12.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-conditional-proof">
        <title>Conditional Proof (CP)</title>
        <p>A proof strategy in which the antecedent of a target conditional is assumed, the consequent is derived, and the assumption is discharged to produce the conditional. (§12.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-contradiction">
        <title>Contradiction (explicit)</title>
        <p>A conjunction of a statement with its own negation (<m>\mathcal{B} \cdot {\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m>), built using Conj inside an IP scope. (§12.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-discharge">
        <title>Discharge</title>
        <p>The step that closes a scope and produces the conclusion licensed by CP or IP. The discharge line cites the scope's line range. (§12.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-indirect-proof">
        <title>Indirect Proof (IP)</title>
        <p>A proof strategy in which the negation of the target is assumed, a contradiction is derived, and the assumption is discharged to produce the negation of the assumption (one tilde prepended). Also called <em>reductio ad absurdum</em>. (§12.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-reductio">
        <title>Reductio ad absurdum</title>
        <p>Latin for <q>reduction to absurdity.</q> Another name for Indirect Proof. (§12.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch12-scope">
        <title>Scope</title>
        <p>The bounded region of a proof, marked by indentation and a vertical line, in which an assumption is active. Lines inside a closed scope cannot be cited afterward. (§12.1)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch12">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch12-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identify the Strategy</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each proof goal, state whether you would try
          Conditional Proof, Indirect Proof, or direct proof, and
          explain your reasoning in one sentence.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>P \supset Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>P</m>, and no premise contains <m>P</m> or a conditional with <m>P</m> as a consequent.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>P \supset R</m>, and the premises include <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>Q \supset R</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, and the premises include <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch12-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Complete the CP Proof</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each proof has the scope opened for you. Supply the
          missing lines inside the scope and the discharge line.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>5.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>

            <row><cell>6.</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset Q</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>

            <row><cell>5.</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>(P \cdot R) \supset (Q \cdot S)</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P \cdot R</m></cell><cell>Assume for CP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch12-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Complete the IP Proof</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Each proof has the scope opened for you. Supply the
          missing lines, including the explicit contradiction, the
          discharge, and any cleanup steps.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \lor Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row bottom="minor"><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>

            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| <m>P</m></cell><cell>Assume for IP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><nbsp/><nbsp/><nbsp/>| </cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch12-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Full Proofs</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Prove each argument valid. You may use any of the eighteen
          rules, CP, and IP.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset (Q \cdot R)</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \supset Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-04">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-05">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset (Q \supset R)</m></cell><cell>/ <m>(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-s04-06">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch12-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 12-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch12-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to your account from Field Exercise 12-1.
            Compare the experience of proving something directly
            (with the eighteen rules alone) to proving something
            by temporarily assuming. Does the assumption strategy
            feel like <q>cheating</q>? Does it feel more natural?
            What does it mean to <em>assume the opposite</em> of
            what you want to prove and then show that it blows up?
            Write a short reflection on what Indirect Proof reveals
            about the relationship between contradiction and truth.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
